        "Ralph Vaughn House at 1212 Westchester Place": "Architect: Ralph Vaughn. Significance: This site is significant for its association with Ralph Vaughn, one of Los Angeles' most influential early African-American architects. Vaughn was a pioneer in the design of large-scale, high-density housing complexes and worked on numerous significant projects across the city, including the Lincoln Heights and Venice areas.",
        "Roscoe's House of Chicken and Waffles": "A legendary Southern California institution and a central social anchor for the region's diverse creative community.",
        "St. Elmo Art Collective": "A 1969-founded art sanctuary and bungalow colony; a landmark of community-driven creative preservation.",
        "The Marvin Gaye House": "A massive, once-stately mansion where the legendary soul singer was tragically shot and killed by his own father in 1984. The house has since fallen into various states of repair, standing as a quiet, residential monument to one of the most tragic days in music history.",
        "The Murder House \u2014 American Horror Story (Rosenheim Mansion)": "Known in real life as the Rosenheim Mansion, this looming property in the Arlington Heights neighborhood was the centerpiece of the first season of American Horror Story. It has a notoriously spooky reputation both on and off the screen.",
        "The Rosenheim Mansion (Murder House)": "Architect: Alfred F. Rosenheim (built 1908). A three-story, 15,000-square-foot Collegiate Gothic-style mansion. It is widely recognized as the \"Murder House\" from the first season of American Horror Story. The estate features a private chapel, a recording studio (formerly a pilot\u2019s lounge), and Tiffany stained-glass windows.",
        "Vineyard Recreation Center": "A local Mid-City park and facility offering basketball, youth programs, and a community meeting room.",
        "Washington Irving Branch Library": "A key civic and historical repository serving the Mid-City and West Adams neighborhoods since the mid-20th century."
