    "palos-verdes-peninsula": {
        "Chadwick School": "Founded in 1937, this prestigious independent school sits atop the Palos Verdes Peninsula, offering sprawling views of the LA Basin. While a private campus, its rolling, wooded grounds define much of the bucolic character of the surrounding Academy Hill community."
    },
    "panorama-city": {
        "Curacao (La Curacao)": "While technically on the border, its massive Mayan-inspired architecture is a visual landmark often used in transition shots to establish a San Fernando Valley setting.",
        "Dr. Hogly Wogly's Tyler Texas BBQ": "Dr. Hogly Wogly\u2019s Tyler Texas BBQ, a world-famous Valley institution founded in 1969 by Johnny Greene. It is widely considered one of the best barbecue spots in Los Angeles, known for its Texas-style brisket and massive portions served on half-loaves of freshly baked bread.",
        "Kaiser Permanente Medical Center (Grey's Anatomy)": "One of the most frequently used hospital sets in the San Fernando Valley, featured in Grey's Anatomy and films like The 40-Year-Old Virgin.",
        "Mia\u2019s Apartment (La La Land)": "Film: Mia\u2019s apartment in La La Land.",
        "Panorama City Wal-Mart (Superstore)": "This location served as the primary setting for the pilot of the NBC sitcom Superstore.",
        "Panorama Mall Master Plan Area": "Part of the original 1955 Panorama Mall master plan, which was one of the first planned communities in the United States designed to integrate massive commercial development with post-war housing.",
        "Sputnik Building": "Known as the Sputnik Building (or the \"Kings of Credit\" building), this 1957 structure is a rare and eccentric example of Space Age architecture. Originally a Savings & Loan, it is famous for its futuristic \"Sputnik\" details and its appearance in the 2002 film Stealing Harvard.",
        "St. Genevieve High School (The Benchwarmers)": "Used for various \"All-American\" high school shots in teen dramas and films, most notably The Benchwarmers.",
        "The Panorama Mall": "The Panorama Mall, originally opened in 1955 as the \"Broadway-Valley\" shopping center. The primary anchor building (now Walmart) was designed by the iconic architectural firm Welton Becket & Associates, the same firm behind the Capitol Records Building and the Music Center.",
        "The Panorama Theatre": "The Panorama Theatre, a historic 1949 movie palace designed by the legendary architect William L. Pereira (famous for the Transamerica Pyramid and LAX). The building is a designated landmark featuring a striking vertical neon tower; a time capsule containing 1940s memorabilia like bobby socks and photos of Frank Sinatra is reportedly buried in its foundation.",
        "The Panorama Towers (Mad Men)": "A mid-century high-rise office building designed by Welton Becket that appeared in numerous productions, including Mad Men, for its period-accurate 1960s aesthetic.",
        "Van Nuys Blvd Cruising Stretch": "This location sits along the historic \"Van Nuys Blvd Cruising\" stretch. During the 1960s and 70s, this specific corridor was the epicenter of Southern California car culture, where thousands would gather to show off custom \"wheels.\"",
        "Van Nuys Boulevard (Boulevard Nights)": "The stretch of the boulevard through Panorama City was a focal point for the 1979 film Boulevard Nights, capturing authentic local lowrider and cruising culture."
    },
