    "playa-del-rey": {
        "Dockweiler State Beach": "Park/Facility in Playa del Rey",
        "Surfridge (Abandoned Neighborhood)": "Once an elite 1920s enclave of Spanish-style mansions favored by Hollywood celebrities like Cecil B. DeMille, Surfridge was slowly consumed by the expansion of LAX and the unbearable noise of jet engines. By the 1970s, all homes had been demolished or relocated. Today it is a 'ghost neighborhood' where paved streets, curbs, and original streetlights remain intact, but no houses stand. The area is now a protected habitat for the El Segundo Blue Butterfly and is strictly off-limits to the public.",
        "The Harbor Room": "One of the smallest bars in the county, this tiny, windowless maritime haunt has been a fixture since the 1930s. It is a time capsule of \"Old Playa,\" where the wood is dark, the drinks are stiff, and the space feels like the belly of an old ship.",
        "The Shack": "Classic beachside dude-food restaurant and bar in Playa del Rey."
    },
    "playa-vista": {
        "Google Spruce Goose (Playa Vista Campus)": "A landmark of adaptive reuse, transforming Howard Hughes' historic 1943 aviation hangar \u2014 originally built to house the H-4 Hercules 'Spruce Goose' wooden aircraft \u2014 into a massive 450,000 sq ft modern workspace for Google, redesigned by ZGF Architects in 2018. The structure is one of the largest clear-span wooden buildings ever constructed, built with 75-foot glulam (glued-laminated) arches due to WWII steel shortages. Before Google, the space served as a film soundstage for Titanic and Avatar. The interior employs a 'building-within-a-building' concept with four terraced floor plates, a central 'boardwalk,' and 'The Ghost of the Goose,' a sculpture of 2,800 suspended steel balls shaped like the original aircraft. The exterior features a forest of 700 poplar trees for phytoremediation.",
        "Nike": "Nike",
        "SCI-Arc (Former Site)": "Former location of the Southern California Institute of Architecture before its move to the Arts District."
    },
