        "Bogdanovich Recreation Center": "Park/Facility in San Pedro",
        "Cabrillo Marine Aquarium": "A major public complex designed by Frank Gehry in 1981, featuring chain-link fencing enclosures that foreshadowed his later style.",
        "Fort MacArthur Museum": "Housed within the historic Battery Osgood-Farley, this museum preserves the history of the U.S. Army post that guarded the Los Angeles harbor from 1914 to 1974. It showcases military fortifications, including the original supports for 14-inch \"disappearing rifles,\" and features a vast collection of photographs, drawings, and memorabilia detailing coastal defense efforts through World War II and the Cold War.",
        "Korean Friendship Bell": "This massive 17-ton bronze bell was presented by South Korea to the United States in 1976 to celebrate the U.S. Bicentennial and symbolize friendship between the two nations. It is modeled after the Divine Bell of King Seongdeok and is housed in a traditional pagoda-style pavilion known as the Belfry of Friendship, which features a roof supported by twelve columns representing the Korean zodiac.",
        "Little Italy (San Pedro)": "Location: Downtown San Pedro (around 6th and 7th Streets).\\n\\nStatus: Official. San Pedro is home to the largest enclave of Italian Americans in Los Angeles. The \"Little Italy\" designation was officially recognized recently (2021\u20132022), and it features the Piazza Miramare and numerous historic Italian social clubs and delis.",
        "Los Angeles Yacht Club": "A historic maritime institution established in 1901, anchoring the nautical and sailing community of the Port of Los Angeles.",
        "Marine Mammal Care Center": "This non-profit hospital rescues and rehabilitates sick and injured seals and sea lions found along the Los Angeles County coastline. Visitors can observe the recovery of \"finned patients,\" such as elephant seals and California sea lions, in outdoor pools and explore educational exhibits about marine mammal conservation.",
        "Maritime Museum (Ferry Building)": "The historic transit hub for the waterfront workforce; preserving the maritime labor history of the 1940s.",
        "Norwegian Seamen's Church": "A unique religious and cultural landmark serving the Scandinavian community and maritime workers of the Port of Los Angeles since the 1940s.",
        "Peck Park": "Park/Facility in San Pedro",
        "Personal Involvement Center": "A social services hub in South Los Angeles focused on family support, youth development, and community empowerment.",
        "Point Fermin Landslide Site": "The epicenter of the 1929 landslide where the ground dropped up to 11 inches per day, creating the current post-apocalyptic terrain.",
        "Point Fermin Lighthouse": "Built in 1874, this Victorian Stick Style lighthouse was the first navigational beacon to guide ships into San Pedro Bay. It features gabled roofs, decorative cross beams, and hand-carved porch railings. The structure was blacked out during World War II and served as a U.S. Navy lookout tower before being restored and placed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1974.",
        "Point Fermin Park (Some Kind of Wonderful)": "The location of the \"art gallery\" date and the final emotional showdown.",
        "Saint Peter's Episcopal Church": "A historic Episcopal church serving the San Pedro waterfront community, reflecting the deep religious and cultural life of this working-class port neighborhood.",
        "San Pedro Municipal Building": "1920s civic structure famous for the 'twist' walk in The Usual Suspects.",
        "Sunken City": "This site contains the ruins of a coastal neighborhood that began sliding into the ocean during a devastating 1929 landslide. Today, it is an unstable terrain of gnarled concrete foundations, ruined sidewalks, and vibrant graffiti art. Although it is technically a prohibited \"No Trespassing\" zone, it is a well-known local destination famous for its post-apocalyptic atmosphere and appearance in the film The Big Lebowski.",
        "Terminal Island Docks (Dexter Filming Site)": "This memorial honors a thriving community of over 3,000 Japanese Americans forcibly removed and interned after Pearl Harbor. The memorial highlights the lost \"Furusato\" (hometown) and the community's role in establishing America's tuna industry. Located in the heart of the Port of Los Angeles, this area is historic for its connection to the fishing and canning industries of \"Fish Harbor.\"",
        "The Ghost Tracks": "Remnants of the Pacific Electric Railway tracks that once ran along the bluff, now twisted and ending abruptly at the cliff edge.",
        "The Usual Suspects Police Station Site": "Film: Police station in The Usual Suspects.",
