    "university-park": {
        "_neighborhood": "The area surrounding the USC campus.",
        "Alfred J. Salisbury Residence (1891)": "A masterpiece of the Queen Anne style, the Salisbury Residence is celebrated for its sweeping wrap-around porch and distinctive corner tower. This grand home captures the transitional spirit of the 1890s, blending refined Victorian details with a massive, commanding presence that remains one of the most photographed landmarks in the University Park neighborhood.",
        "Automobile Club of Southern California": "A 1923 Spanish Colonial Revival landmark that served as the headquarters of the Automobile Club of Southern California, one of the most powerful organizations shaping the car-centric development of Los Angeles. It represents the foundational role of the automobile in defining the city's geography and culture.",
        "Casa de Rosas Campus": "A historic campus that has served variously as a private school, an inn, and a refuge for the homeless.",
        "Felix Chevrolet Sign": "Towering over the 110 freeway near downtown Los Angeles, the massive three-sided neon sign featuring Felix the Cat has been a beloved beacon for commuters since 1958. Felix the Cat was licensed to the dealership's original owner, Winslow Felix, who was friends with the character's creator, Pat Sullivan. The sign is deeply ingrained in LA's car culture and is one of the largest and most famous neon automotive signs on the West Coast. The dealership itself has been operating since the 1920s, making it one of the oldest in the city.",
        "Glen Lukens Home and Studio (1940) \u2014 HCM #866": "The Vibe: Designed for the world-renowned ceramicist Glen Lukens. This is a rare industrial-residential hybrid. The studio was built specifically to accommodate Lukens' massive kilns and experimental pottery work.\n\nGazetteer Note: Unlike the hillside glass boxes, this is a more grounded, \"working-class\" modernist structure. It proves Soriano\u2019s belief that steel could be utilized for utilitarian, creative spaces just as effectively as for luxury homes.",
        "Historic Districts": "Includes University Park HPOZ, North University Park Historic District, and St. James Park Historic District.",
        "Holbox": "2025 Outstanding Chef James Beard Foundation Award Winner. Chef Gilberto Cetina Jr.'s Michelin-starred Yucatan seafood specialist inside the Mercado La Paloma food hall.",
        "Hoover Recreation Center": "Park/Facility in University Park",
        "John C. Harrison House (1891)": "This striking Queen Anne Victorian stands as a premier example of 19th-century elegance, featuring the intricate woodwork and asymmetrical silhouettes that defined the era's opulent residential architecture. As a contributing property to the North University Park Historic District, it serves as a beautifully preserved anchor for a streetscape that once housed Los Angeles' social elite.",
        "Menlo Avenue-West 29th St Historic District": "Recognized as a Historic District with significant early 20th-century residential architecture.",
        "Paul Revere Williams House": "Historic residence on W 35th St associated with architect Paul R. Williams.",
        "Shrine Auditorium": "Massive Moorish Revival performance venue built in 1926.",
        "The Velaslavasay Panorama": "Quirky exhibition hall presents historic panorama paintings, plus living gardens & live events.",
        "Thomas Churchill Mansion (Arbuckle/Bara)": "A grand historic mansion famously associated with silent film stars Roscoe 'Fatty' Arbuckle and the legendary 'vamp' Theda Bara. It reflects the era when West Adams was the premier residential district for early Hollywood royalty.",
        "W.W. Cockins House (1894)": "Designed by the prominent architectural firm Bradbeer & Ferris, this 5,570-square-foot Queen Anne manor is a designated Los Angeles Historic-Cultural Monument (#519). Beyond its architectural pedigree, the house holds a place in Hollywood lore as a rumored temporary residence for Charlie Chaplin in 1913, adding a layer of cinematic history to its Victorian grandeur.",
        "Widney Hall (USC)": "The oldest university building in Southern California, built in 1880 as the first home of the University of Southern California. The modest Eastlake Victorian structure is a stark contrast to the modern campus that surrounds it, serving as a founding monument of higher education in Los Angeles."
    },
