        "Coop Himmelblau House (513 Grand)": "An avant-garde residential design by the renowned Austrian firm, representing the deconstructivist influence on Venice architectural landscape.",
        "Dogtown (Historic)": "The History: \"Dogtown\" refers to a historic geographic area spanning South Santa Monica and Venice. In the 1970s, this gritty, declining coastal neighborhood birthed a revolution in youth culture.\n\nCultural Significance: It was the stomping ground for the legendary Z-Boys (Zephyr Competition Team), who pioneered aggressive, surf-inspired skateboarding. Utilizing empty swimming pools during the California droughts, these local teens transformed skateboarding from a niche hobby into a global action-sports phenomenon.",
        "El Bordello Alexandra": "This is the site of El Bordello Alexandra, one of the most visually striking apartment buildings in Los Angeles. Features a massive collection of demonic leering gargoyles, life-sized warrior-woman statues, and vibrant murals. The building was transformed by owners Tony Wells and Brittany Stevenson from a dilapidated structure into a \"bizarre\" landmark intended to serve as a communal creative crash pad for artists and musicians.",
        "First Baptist Church of Venice": "Historic Black church in the Oakwood neighborhood of Venice.",
        "Historic Venice Beach Home (Clad in Hollywood Bowl Benches)": "An outstanding Venice beach home, fully renovated on a rare double lot. The original Hollywood Bowl benches from 1919 clad the home exterior.",
        "Irvin Tabor Family Residences": "Homes owned by Irvin Tabor, an African American who worked as Abbot Kinney's chauffeur and inherited properties in Venice.",
        "Jim Morrison Historical Site": "A historical site associated with Jim Morrison of The Doors.",
        "John Baldessari\u2019s former Venice studio": "This property served as the studio and gallery for the groundbreaking conceptual artist John Baldessari. It represents a vital, creative piece of the vibrant Venice contemporary art scene.",
        "Mosaic Tile House": "This quirky 1940s home has been covered inside & out with colored tile & splintered-glass mosaics.",
        "Spiller House": "A striking early example of Frank Gehry's corrugated metal aesthetic, consisting of two dense vertical living spaces.",
        "The Eames Original Offices (The 901 Studio)": "This location is historically significant as the Eames Original Offices (the 901 Studio). Served as the creative headquarters for legendary designers Charles and Ray Eames from 1943 until 1988. It was the birthplace of some of the most influential designs of the 20th century, including the Eames Lounge Chair and their groundbreaking film and exhibition work. Abbot Kinney Boulevard itself is now world-famous as a premier destination for high-end boutique shopping and produce-forward dining.",
