        "Dandelion Ranch": "Community garden and urban farm on W Jefferson Blvd.",
        "Doheny Mansion": "A sprawling French Chateau-style estate built in 1899 for oil magnate Edward L. Doheny, located within the Chester Place gated community near USC. The mansion and its grounds represent the opulent peak of West Adams as L.A.'s wealthiest residential district. Now part of Mount Saint Mary's University.",
        "Fisher & Sons Funeral Home (Six Feet Under)": "A stunning Queen Anne Victorian serving as the iconic Fisher family home and funeral parlor in the HBO series Six Feet Under.",
        "Golden State Mutual Life Building (Paul R. Williams)": "1948 by Paul R. Williams at Western Ave & Adams Blvd. A significant monument to Black corporate success in the mid-century.",
        "Guasti Villa / Busby Berkeley Estate": "Built in 1910 by an Italian wine magnate, this spectacular Beaux-Arts villa was later owned by legendary Hollywood choreographer Busby Berkeley. Today, it serves as the Peace Awareness Labyrinth & Gardens, an unexpected spiritual oasis in the city.",
        "Hauerwaas Residence": "Notable historic residence on W 27th St in West Adams.",
        "J-N-J Burger & Bar-b-que": "Local burger and BBQ joint on W Adams Blvd.",
        "Johnny's Pastrami on Adams": "Classic LA pastrami stand on W Adams Blvd.",
        "Kinney Heights": "Developed in 1900 by Abbot Kinney, featuring custom-built Craftsman mansions.",
        "Kobbler King": "Local cobbler and shoe repair on W Jefferson Blvd.",
        "London Shop Barber Shop": "Long-standing local barbershop on W Adams Blvd.",
        "Longstreet's 'Palm Avenue'": "Located near the corner of West Adams Boulevard and Flower Street, this row of 23 Mexican Fan Palms (Washingtonia robusta) constitutes some of the oldest living residents of Los Angeles. They represent the very beginning of the city's transformation into a \"palm-guarded\" Mediterranean oasis.\n\nOrigins: These trees were planted around 1875 by Charles Longstreet, a wealthy New Yorker (and distant relative of Confederate General James Longstreet) who moved to Los Angeles for his health. He established a 35-acre estate called L'Orangerie.\n\nThe Driveway: The palms originally lined the grand private driveway that led from Adams Boulevard to the Longstreet mansion. At the time, this area was the \"hinterlands\" of the city, dominated by orchards and sprawling estates.\n\nSignificance: While Los Angeles is now synonymous with palm trees, they are not native to the L.A. Basin. Longstreet's \"Palm Avenue\" was one of the first major ornamental plantings that helped establish the palm as a symbol of Southern California luxury and exoticism.\n\nThe Site Today: Though the mansion is long gone, the trees were preserved when the land was donated to the Orthopaedic Institute for Children (OIC) in the 1920s. Today, they stand nearly 100 feet tall, visible from the nearby 110 Freeway, serving as a biological \"ghost\" of the Victorian-era estates that once defined the West Adams district.",
        "Loyola High School (Donnie Darko Filming Location)": "Loyola High School, used as the high school filming location in the 2001 cult film Donnie Darko.",
        "Mariscos Maria's Restaurant": "Seafood restaurant on W Adams Blvd.",
        "Marvin Gaye Estate": "A historic residence famously the home of Motown legend Marvin Gaye during the 1970s. It stands as an important piece of musical and cultural history within the greater West Adams area.",
        "Masjid Abu Bakr As-Siddiq": "Local mosque on Crenshaw Blvd.",
        "McWorld (Art Venue)": "Art venue and gathering space on W Adams Blvd.",
        "Natural History Museum of L.A. County": "A 1913 Beaux-Arts landmark in Exposition Park; a cornerstone of the city's scientific and architectural heritage.",
        "Nick Metropolis (Collectibles & Antiques)": "Eclectic antiques and collectibles shop on W Adams Blvd.",
        "NTBA Gallery": "Local art gallery on W 25th St.",
        "Old Janitor Supply Ghost Sign": "Surviving ghost sign for the 'Old Janitor Supply' painted on the building facade.",
        "Pete's Louisiana Style Hot Links": "Classic Louisiana-style hot links restaurant on W Jefferson Blvd.",
        "Phillips BBQ": "Legendary West Adams BBQ institution on Crenshaw Blvd.",
        "Pineapple Express Red's House Filming Location": "The house used as Red's home in the 2008 film Pineapple Express.",
        "Ralph Bunche House": "The childhood home of the first African American Nobel Peace Prize winner; a key site of social history.",
        "Redeemer Baptist Church": "Historic Baptist church on W Jefferson Blvd.",
        "Rindge Estate": "Historic estate associated with the Rindge family on S Harvard Blvd.",
        "Rindge-Frederick Hastings House": "A significant West Adams estate reflecting the grand residential ambitions of early 20th-century Los Angeles, part of the historic corridor of landmark homes that made West Adams the premier address in the city before World War II.",
        "RPM International (Ray Charles Studio)": "The legendary recording studio and headquarters built by Ray Charles in 1962. Blending modernism with a fortress-like exterior, this hidden creative powerhouse was where the Genius of Soul recorded some of his greatest work.",
        "Saint Vincent de Paul Church": "A 1925 Spanish Churrigueresque baroque masterpiece designed by Albert C. Martin Sr. Its ornate facade and soaring interior are considered some of the finest examples of Catholic church architecture in the United States. A spiritual anchor of the Adams Boulevard corridor.",
        "Second Church of Christ Scientist": "A monumental Beaux-Arts temple on the Adams corridor, representative of the grand civic and religious architecture built for West Adams' wealthy turn-of-the-century residents.",
        "South Seas House": "Distinctive Polynesian Revival residential property on W 24th St.",
        "St. James Park Historic District": "A turn-of-the-century residential enclave surrounding a private park, once home to the city social elite.",
        "Synchronicity Intentional Community": "Cooperative intentional community on Westmoreland Blvd.",
        "The Giraffe House": "Residential property named for its distinctive giraffe-themed exterior decor.",
        "The House Bunny Sorority House Filming Location": "The house used as the sorority house in the 2008 film The House Bunny.",
        "The Lyfe (Graphic Design & Designer Clothes)": "Local graphic design studio and designer clothing shop on Jefferson Blvd.",
        "The Wilfandel Club": "Founded in 1926 by prominent Black women including Della Williams (wife of architect Paul R. Williams), it is the oldest African American women's club in Los Angeles. It remains a vital community hub and a pillar of the 'Sugar Hill' legacy.",
        "The Witwicky House (Transformers Filming Location)": "The house used as the Witwicky family home in the 2007 film Transformers.",
        "Vineyard Recreation Center": "Park/Facility in West Adams / Mid-City",
        "Washington Carburetors": "Local auto parts and carburetor shop on W Adams Blvd.",
        "William Andrews Clark Memorial Library": "Built in 1926 and donated to UCLA, the Clark Library is a world-class research library housed in a spectacular Italian Renaissance Revival building. Its collection of rare books, including a major collection of Oscar Wilde manuscripts, is internationally significant. The surrounding formal garden is a masterpiece of early 20th-century landscape design."
