        "Kike\u2019s Tacos": "Pronounced \"Kee-Kay\" (a common Spanish nickname for Enrique). It\u2019s a staple for the local Crown Hill/Temple-Beaudry area.",
        "Langer\u2019s Deli": "An L.A. institution since 1947, Langer's is widely regarded as serving the best pastrami sandwich in the country. Located across from MacArthur Park, it has survived and thrived through the neighborhood's many transformations and remains a beloved anchor of Westlake.",
        "Lewis House": "A rare Queen Anne Victorian (HCM #39) designed by Joseph Cather Newsom in 1890. It\u2019s a survivor of the era when Westlake was the 'Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es' of Los Angeles.",
        "Luma South Park": "A modern high-rise residential building that was a pioneer in the sustainable \"Green\" development movement in Downtown Los Angeles.",
        "MacArthur Park & The MacArthur (Park Plaza Hotel)": "MacArthur Park (formerly Westlake Park) is a historic urban green space featuring a scenic lake and the Levitt Pavilion, which hosts free summer concerts. Adjacent is The MacArthur, formerly the Park Plaza Hotel, a stunning 1925 Neo-Gothic building renowned for its grand ballroom and extensive history as a cinematic backdrop.",
        "McManus & Morgan": "Historic fine paper store operating since 1923.",
        "Metropolis Los Angeles Site": "A major mixed-use development site that has transformed the skyline of Downtown's South Park district.",
        "Olympic Auditorium Area": "Designed by architect Gilbert Stanley Underwood, this 1924 boxing and wrestling arena was a major center for LA sports for decades and a landmark of Downtown's early 20th-century expansion.",
        "Oscar Romero Clinic": "Named after the martyred Archbishop, specifically serving the Westlake community.",
        "Pacific Dining Car": "A legendary 24-hour steakhouse housed in a 1920s railway car, historically favored by city power brokers and classic noir novelists.",
        "Park Plaza Hotel / Elks Lodge No. 99": "Designed by Curlett & Beelman in 1925. It\u2019s a Neo-Gothic/Art Deco hybrid that feels like a cathedral for high society. The interior is famously opulent, used in countless films (like Barton Fink and Drive).",
        "Pico-Union Historic District": "A 1920s-era building in one of LA's most architecturally diverse historic districts, primarily serving the city's early elite and later immigrant communities.",
        "Royal Viking Motel": "Where Hal LeSueur, the estranged brother of movie star Joan Crawford, died in obscurity in 1963. A classic 'Hollywood Fall' story set in a mid-century motel.",
        "Selena Mural (Hector Ponce)": "An iconic neighborhood landmark by Hector Ponce, the master of Westlake's 'celebrity-saint' portraiture.",
        "Silver Platter": "One of Los Angeles' oldest operating gay bars and a haven for the Latinx LGBTQ community.",
        "Sky Lofts at 11th & Hope": "A prominent residential and commercial high-rise that represents the modern \"Live-Work-Play\" philosophy of the South Park revitalization.",
        "St. Thomas the Apostle Church": "Located on the western edge of the district.",
        "The \"V\" Apartment": "Used as a primary filming location for the 1983 sci-fi miniseries V. It represents the neighborhood's frequent use as a stand-in for 'anywhere USA' or 'dystopian urban sprawl.'",
        "The Hite Building / Aardvark Letterpress": "A Morgan, Walls & Clements design featuring intricate Spanish/Churrigueresque ornamentation. Home to Aardvark Letterpress, a sanctuary for high-end typography and printing in the heart of the district.",
        "The Last Oil Well": "A literal oil well hidden in the backyard of a commercial property. A reminder that L.A. was built on 'black gold.'",
        "The Los Angeles Convention Center Area": "A major international landmark that hosts the LA Auto Show and E3, and a cornerstone of the Downtown entertainment district.",
        "Tiny Street": "Quite literally, a street named 'Little Street' that is arguably the smallest in the district.",
        "Tommy\u2019s Original": "The original 24-hour burger shack. It\u2019s a masterpiece of 'car culture' architecture\u2014minimal, functional, and iconic."
