    "wilshire-park": {
        "Wilshire Park HPOZ": "The Context: Designated as a Historic Preservation Overlay Zone (HPOZ) in 2008, Wilshire Park is a remarkably intact residential enclave.\n\nNeighborhood Character: The area is celebrated for its diverse and well-preserved collection of early 20th-century architecture, including Craftsman, Dutch Colonial, Spanish Colonial Revival, and Prairie Style homes. It offers a quieter, residential look at the expansion of Los Angeles during the \"Wilshire boom\" of the 1920s."
    },
    "windsor-square": {
        "Higgins-Verbeck-Hirsch Mansion": "A massive Queen Anne/Craftsman hybrid mansion relocated from Wilshire Blvd to Windsor Square in 1924.",
        "Historic Windsor Square Estate": "Built in 1927 and designed by Robert D. Jones in the Georgian Revival style, this historic estate sits on over a third of an acre. Beyond its grand architectural pedigree, the home boasts a fun piece of 1980s pop culture history: it was featured as Matthew Broderick's house in the 1983 film WarGames. Situated behind mature magnolia trees, the home features wood siding, white brickwork, preserved original wood windows, and a detached guest house. It recently underwent a meticulous restoration that preserved its 1920s grandeur while modernizing the underlying systems.",
        "Los Altos Apartments": "Built in 1926 and designed by Edward B. Rust (with interior contributions reportedly by Julia Morgan), this five-story Spanish Colonial Revival building was hailed by the LA Times as a new standard of luxury. It was the first co-op on the West Coast, serving as a playground for golden-era Hollywood royalty like Bette Davis, Mae West, Douglas Fairbanks, and William Randolph Hearst with his mistress Marion Davies (whose lavish suite was reportedly designed by Julia Morgan). Instantly recognizable by its classic neon rooftop sign, the building features preserved original hardwood floors, intricate moldings, and a grand lobby. It is Los Angeles Historic-Cultural Monument #311.",
        "The Snow White House (Adriana Caselotti Residence)": "Nestled among the historic, meticulously planned streets of Windsor Square and the Larchmont Village shopping district, this uniquely crafted cedar home was designed and built by Adriana Caselotti \u2014 the original voice of Disney's Snow White. Fittingly, the home's architecture is deeply organic, and the front garden features a wooden bridge and a wishing well.",
        "Windsor Square": "Property Type: Quarter"
    },
